@Puzzlemucker 

What a memory (though the references are fairly recent, I think)!

[sigh] And now the unpleasant part.  You may stop here, if you please, dear reader.  To insure any chance of my short comment seeing the light of day, I type and type, (and gripe and gripe) and write this tripe so this comment goes down the pipe.

@Andrew 

Well, POLK was too early, and despite his name, FORD was too late.  So it had to be TAFT.

I don't think there were any other four-letter presidents, but TAFT definitely was around the right time.

@Barry Ancona - as a train-oriented person, I submit that nothing in the USA will ever be efficient as long as “those people” exercise power. Anybody who has ever traveled abroad knows what efficient public transit / high speed rail is, and does for the economy and society.

Nonetheless - once you go south of the District of Columbia - you had better be prepared for your train to arrive in third-world country time. I tried getting to my job in North Carolina by rail, and every single time we passed Union Station, welp, figure on adding six to fourteen hours to your arrival time…

America gets what it votes for. It votes for malfunction 68.3 percent of the time.

@Robert Forbes 

I do know that Oklahomans sometimes call Texas Baja Oklahoma.

But seriously, Oklahoma isn't the "Deep South", but it's definitely in the South.  South Central, to be specific.

@john ezra

